Project: Investigate NICS Firearm Background Checks with FBI Gun Data and Census Data¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

The data comes from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System. The NICS is used by to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Gun shops call into this system to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isn't otherwise ineligible to make a purchase.

Mandated by the Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act of 1993 and launched by the FBI on November 30, 1998, NICS is used by Federal Firearms Licensees (FFLs) to instantly determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Before ringing up the sale, cashiers call in a check to the FBI or to other designated agencies to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isn’t otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. More than 100 million such checks have been made in the last decade, leading to more than 700,000 denials.

Notes on the NICS data¶

The NICS data is found in one sheet of an .xlsx file. It contains the number of firearm checks by month, state, and type.

A one-to-one correlation cannot be made between a firearm background check and a firearm sale.

  • These statistics represent the number of firearm background checks initiated through the NICS They do not represent the number of firearms sold.

Despite some vagaries, the FBI's NICS numbers are widely accepted as the best proxy for total gun sales in a given time period.

  • As seen in the late February-early March 2014 bubble, many checks are for concealed carry permits, not actual gun sales. Kentucky runs a new check on each concealed carry license holder each month. And of course, the FBI's numbers don't include private gun sales, many of which do not require a background check. A forthcoming study conducted by Harvard researchers found that roughly 40 percent of respondents had acquired their most recent firearm without going through a background check.

Because state laws differ, sales levels between states cannot be directly compared.

  • Sales estimates are calculated from handgun, long gun and multiple-gun background checks. Permit checks and other categories of background checks are excluded. In California, multiple-gun checks were excluded because data was inconsistent.

Multipliers on background checks are estimated to project the sales.

  • To convert background checks into estimated sales, we relied on a method suggested in the Small Arms Survey by Jurgen Brauer, a professor at Georgia Regents University. Each long gun and handgun check was counted as 1.1 sales. Each multiple-gun check was counted as two sales. Permit checks and other types of checks were omitted. The multiplier is an estimate based on Mr. Brauer's interviews with gun shop owners.

Original notes and caveats can be found on Github.

Notes on the census data¶

The NICS data has been supplemented with state level census data from census.gov.

  • The U.S. census data is found in a .csv file. It contains several variables at the state level. Most variables just have one data point per state (2016), but a few have data for more than one year.

In this project, I'll first load, check and clean the dataset, and then explore there questions.

  • What census data is most associated with high gun check per capita?
  • Which states have had the highest growth in gun checks?
  • What is the overall trend of gun checks?

In the end, conclusions will be drawn.

I choose year 2016 annual data because census data are given on anual basis, and 50 (states) data points are large enough to get some interesting findings.

Dataframe are divided into two: high and low gun check per capita, and then be compared with census data to study the difference. Then, scatterplot with regression are used to visualize the correlation of gun check per capita and census data. The most associated census data can be observed afterwards.

Conclusions¶

In this project, the investigation are based on NICS firearm background checks with FBI gun data and census data. Although the analysis is tentative, we can have a comprehensive insight on the gun activities in the U.S., and also have some interesting findings as follow.

States of high gun check per capita has higer white people percentage.

Based on the comparison on states of high/low gun check per capita, white people percentage are higher in states of high_gpc, black, hispanic, and asian people percent are higher in states of low_gpc. Also, the states of lower gun check per capita have larger housing units and building permits.

The scatterplots and linear regression models of census data and gun check per capita show the most positive associate census data are white people percentage. Thus, it seems states with higer white percentage will have higher gun check per capita. The other census data such as female, black, asian, hispanic etc. show weak negative correlations with the gun check capita.

There are several things need to be noted of the first question. 1) The analysis does not state or imply that one change causes another based solely on a correlation. The gun activities are influenced by many aspects. Although census association analysis in this project can get some insights of this problem, comprehensive and deeper analysis should consider more. 2) Scatterplots and regression models in DEA can provide intuitive illustration of the correlations of census data and gun check per capita. However, the correlation coefficient and statistical tests are essential for more reliable conclusions. 3) During the investigation, only data of year 2016 are studied due to the census data limitation. With more data from different years, we can conduct more analysis and may get consistent conclusions.

Kentucky has both high gun checks and growth rate

It can be observed that Kentucky is the state of both highest gun check per capita (0.83 in year 2016) and highest average growth rate on gun checks (26.5%, from year 1999 to 2016).Maybe because Kentucky has some of the weakest gun laws in the country. Recent years, the state released its requirement that people obtain a license and background check to carry concealed firearms in public. Other states, like California, Illinois, Texas, Indiana etc.also have both very fast growth rate and amounts of gun checks.

Despite of the truth that Kentucky has both high gun checks and growth rate, there are more information can be further analyzed from the line charts, such as big increase in year 2006 and sharp drop in 2013.There must be some gun related laws, policies or events behind the data.

Gun checks has acccelerated increase since 1998

As noted in the Indrodution, since 1998 November, NICS is used to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Then the gun checks shows an acccelerated increase, which indicates the increased demand of gun related activities.

Obviously, the regplot gives a very fit second order polynomial form of the gun check trends. For more reliable results, statistical analysis such as r-sq, analysis of variance, residual analysis are quite important. What's more, the third question in this project only dipict the history of gun actvities, predictions on the future can be conduct for future study such as the estimate of gun checks in year 2017 (and we do have 9 months data for 2017!).
